    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Debating the Bush Agenda, From Sea to Sea</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Donald L Doernberg letter says this is not time for nation to be throwing itself a big tax-cut party, without paying off national debt we ran up earlier (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''President Unveils $1.96 Trillion Plan That Trims Taxes'' (front page, March 1):</p>
        <p>It comes down to this: we, as a national family, have run up an enormous debt, much of which came from the huge Reagan tax cut. This is not an appropriate time for us to throw ourselves a big party by way of a tax cut when we should be paying down that debt.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''President Unveils $1.96 Trillion Plan That Trims Taxes'' (front page, March 1):</p>
        <p>It comes down to this: we, as a national family, have run up an enormous debt, much of which came from the huge Reagan tax cut. This is not an appropriate time for us to throw ourselves a big party by way of a tax cut when we should be paying down that debt.</p>
        <p>If a private family were greatly in debt and, instead of paying down the debt, went out and bought an expensive new car, how sympathetic would we be when the overly indebted family sought public assistance? That's the microcosm; the president's tax cut leads inevitably to the macrocosm, just as the Reagan tax cut did.</p>
        <p>DONALD L. DOERNBERG  White Plains, March 1, 2001</p>
      </block>
